Very Important Interview Point

A toleration does not force a Pod onto a node.

It only permits the Pod to run there.

Example:

Cluster:

Node1

Node2 (gpu=true)

Pod:

Has gpu toleration

Scheduler may still choose:

Node1

because toleration is only permission, not a placement rule.

How do you force a Pod onto a specific node?

Use Node Affinity or Node Selector together with taints.

Example:

Node

gpu=true

↓

Taint:
gpu=true:NoSchedule

↓

Label:
gpu=true

↓

Pod

NodeAffinity:
gpu=true

Toleration:
gpu=true

Now:

Node Affinity selects the GPU node.
Toleration allows the Pod onto the tainted node.

This combination is common in production.

Remove a taint
kubectl taint nodes worker-2 gpu=true:NoSchedule-

Notice the trailing -.

Check again:

kubectl describe node worker-2

The taint should be gone.

Built-in Taints

Kubernetes automatically applies some taints.

Node Not Ready
node.kubernetes.io/not-ready
Node Unreachable
node.kubernetes.io/unreachable
Memory Pressure
node.kubernetes.io/memory-pressure
Disk Pressure
node.kubernetes.io/disk-pressure
PID Pressure
node.kubernetes.io/pid-pressure

These help prevent new Pods from being scheduled onto unhealthy nodes.

Real Production Examples
1. GPU Nodes
gpu=true:NoSchedule

Only ML/AI workloads with the proper toleration run there.

2. Database Nodes
database=true:NoSchedule

Only database Pods can be scheduled.

3. Monitoring Nodes
monitoring=true:NoSchedule

Only monitoring tools like Prometheus or Grafana agents run there.

4. Spot Instances
spot=true:NoSchedule

Only workloads that can tolerate interruptions are scheduled.

Interview Questions
Q1. What is a taint?

A taint is applied to a Node to repel Pods unless they have a matching toleration.

Q2. What is a toleration?

A toleration is applied to a Pod to allow it to be scheduled on a tainted node.

Q3. Does a toleration guarantee scheduling on a tainted node?

No. It only allows scheduling. Use Node Affinity or Node Selector to prefer or require a specific node.

Q4. Difference between NoSchedule and NoExecute?
NoSchedule: Blocks new Pods only.
NoExecute: Blocks new Pods and evicts existing Pods that don't tolerate the taint.
Hands-on Lab (Recommended)

To truly understand taints and tolerations, practice this sequence:

Create a namespace:

kubectl create namespace taint-demo
Taint one of your worker nodes with NoSchedule.
Deploy an NGINX Pod without a toleration and observe it stay in Pending.

Describe the Pod:

kubectl describe pod <pod-name> -n taint-demo

Look for an event like:

node(s) had untolerated taint
Add the matching toleration to the Pod manifest and redeploy.
Change the taint effect to NoExecute and observe how existing Pods behave.

Working through these steps will make the scheduling behavior much easier to remember than just reading the theory.
